<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="153" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1302,1689]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,1302,1328]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Colony a curved, unbranched whip. Polyps contain eight long, individual tentacular needles that form a distinctive V-shape surrounding the tentacles, with very few sclerites in the polyp basal section. The axis is covered by a thick coenenchyme. The polyp body consists of two parts, which may be separated by a conspicuous bend in the body midway along the length. The tentacles contain long, thin rods, and sclerites of the pharynx are elongated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,891,1446,1473]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153" type="type_taxon">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1302,1689]" box="[199,891,1446,1473]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,347,1446,1472]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">
<typeStatus box="[199,258,1446,1472]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">Type</typeStatus>
species
</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName authority="Lapointe &amp; Watling, 2022" authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[361,587,1446,1472]" class="Anthozoa" family="Keratoisididae" genus="Tanyostea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="153" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="wolverini" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[361,587,1446,1472]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">Tanyostea wolverini</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[594,731,1446,1473]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
, by monotypy
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="153" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1302,1689]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1482,1508]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">Remarks</emphasis>
. The segmented polyp body, bending abaxially, and the V-shaped arrangement of intertentacular sclerites are unique characters attributed to this genus. As noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Watling, L. &amp; Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C." box="[900,1131,1518,1545]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153" pagination="337 - 375" refId="ref9546" refString="Watling, L. Heestand Saucier, E. &amp; France, S. C. (2022) Towards a revision of the bamboo corals: Part 4, delineating the family Keratoisididae. Zootaxa, 5093 (3), 337 - 375. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 5093.3.4" type="journal article" year="2022">Watling et al. (2022)</bibRefCitation>
unbranched colonies occur in several clades of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gray" authorityYear="1870" box="[425,592,1554,1580]" class="Anthozoa" family="Keratoisididae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="153" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="family">Keratoisididae</taxonomicName>
. This new genus, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lapointe &amp; Watling" authorityYear="2022" box="[799,912,1555,1580]" class="Anthozoa" family="Keratoisididae" genus="Tanyostea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="16" pageNumber="153" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[799,912,1555,1580]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">Tanyostea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is representative of clade C1 (
<figureCitation box="[1271,1342,1554,1580]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[415,1180,182,1919]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[393,1195,181,1919]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 2. Cladogram of the Keratoisididae modified from Watling et al. (2022). New taxa added in this paper are in bold lettering. Bootstrap values&gt;50 are shown above the nodes and Bayesian probability values&gt;0.5 are shown below the nodes. Major clades are referred to by the designation along the right side of the cladogram." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6877167" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6877167/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), all the known members of which are characterized by having unbranched colonies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="153" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1302,1689]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1626,1652]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">Etymology</emphasis>
. The genus name is based on the Greek adjective 
<emphasis box="[889,937,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">tany</emphasis>
= long, and the noun 
<emphasis box="[1183,1256,1627,1652]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">osteon</emphasis>
= bone, a reference to the long internodes of the axial skeleton that characterize the 
<typeStatus box="[926,974,1663,1689]" pageId="16" pageNumber="153">type</typeStatus>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
